article.description: The Spurs spoiled the first NBA playoff game in Memphis by holding off the Grizzlies for a 3-0 series lead.

images.name: Parker Tony 040425 332x170
images.caption: Tony Parker and the Spurs brushed aside the Grizzlies.

related.title: Heisley fulfills early-season promise

article.headline: Spurs can sweep series Sunday
article.linkText: Grizzlies fight, but can't contain Spurs
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Hedo Turkoglu held his breath from the instant the Memphis Grizzlies inbounded the ball with 3.6 seconds left. He and the rest of the San Antonio Spurs exhaled when Mike Miller's 3-point attempt bounced off the back rim as the buzzer sounded. That preserved a 95-93 victory Thursday night for the Spurs who are well on their way to sweeping into the second round. Tim Duncan scored 10 of his 22 points in the fourth quarter, and the defending champions spoiled the first NBA playoff game in Memphis by taking a 3-0 lead in their first-round series. Turkoglu was right beside Miller as he launched the possible game-winner. "It was a good shot you know. Thank God it didn't go in," he said. The Spurs won their 14th straight game by holding off a Memphis team that fed off a sellout crowd of 19,351 that greeted them with a standing ovation and towels waving. Why, Memphis even had five guys dressed as Elvis for a history-making game no one could have imagined before this franchise relocated here from Vancouver in 2001. But it wasn't enough against one of the NBA's best teams at home or on the road. Miller said he practices that shot every day and that it just didn't go in this night. Duncan had flashbacks to Stephon Marbury hitting an almost identical shot to beat the Spurs in Game 1 of their first-round series last season, and Manu Ginobili said he thought it was going in. "In these games, anybody can win. Both worked really hard. We probably both really deserved it, and on the last shot, anything can happen," Ginobili said. Turkoglu hit his first seven shots and finished with 18 points for the Spurs, while Tony Parker added 18 points and six assists, and Ginobili had 12 points. Memphis easily had its best performance in the playoffs, but it didn't matter as the Grizzlies lost their seventh straight game. Pau Gasol led the Grizzlies with 18 points, Jason Williams had 16, Bonzi Wells 14 and Miller 12. "We did one thing well, and we grounded it out," San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said. "The defense was fantastic, and they were physical, and they attacked us for 48 minutes. I just think we were really fortunate to come up with the victory." The Spurs can clinch this seven-game series Sunday night here in Game 4. "We don't want to get swept. So we have to come out here with guns blazing on Sunday and play as hard as we did tonight," Miller said. San Antonio blew out Memphis in the first two games of this series but never led by more than six points Thursday. Duncan scored with 1:37 left to put the Spurs ahead to stay at 92-91. Ginobili hit the second of two free throws with 3.6 seconds left for the final margin. NBA Coach of the Year Hubie Brown knows his Grizzlies had plenty of chances to win. "Down the stretch, we had five possessions and only one score," Brown said. "We missed four shots and had one turnover." Duncan, who averaged 24.5 points in the first two games, found it tougher to find the basket with Lorenzen Wright, Stromile Swift and Gasol all taking turns guarding him. He had only 12 points through the first three quarters and finally broke out in the fourth. Memphis finally shook off its shooting woes and hit 48.7 percent from the field. The Grizzlies still couldn't control the boards, and San Antonio outrebounded them 48-31. The Grizzlies led by as many as 10 points twice. But Brown had his Grizzlies so focused on sticking with Parker, who had 27 points in Game 2, that the Spurs guard kept dishing off to teammates for wide-open 3s in the corners. Turkoglu hit two 3-pointers at the end of the first quarter to put San Antonio up 29-28, and the Spurs took advantage of the Grizzlies' tight defense in the paint to go 7-of-9 on 3s early. Memphis finally cooled off in the third quarter and hit just 5-of-16 from the field. San Antonio started hitting the boards and outrebounded the Grizzlies 18-8. When Turkoglu hit his fourth 3-pointer at 8:16 of the third, he gave the Spurs a 62-61 lead that was their first since the end of the first quarter.

Game notes
The Grizzlies had been 36-2 when tied or leading after the third quarter. ... Duncan was called for a technical foul in the second quarter after arguing a no-call on a drive inside. ... Memphis turned the ball over 34 times in the first two games but had just seven in Game 3 while forcing 15.
